Joins in R

Its rare that a data analysis involves only a single table (data frame). Typically you have many tables (data frames), and you must join them together to answer the questions that youre interested in.

Let us work with flights. I am choosing to load a sample from github instead of the nycflights13 package because nycflights13 is not working for one of your fellow students.

Joins in R

One of the issues with the flights data is that it doesnt have the carrier names. The carrier variable is limited to the two-digit airline symbol. But there is another table (airlines table) that has a similar carrier variable with the carrier name fully spelled out:

airlines <- read_rds("https://github.com/jmtfeliciano/teachingdata/raw/refs/heads/main/airlines.rds")
head(airlines)
## # A tibble: 6  2
##   carrier name                    
##   <chr>   <chr>                   
## 1 9E      Endeavor Air Inc.       
## 2 AA      American Airlines Inc.  
## 3 AS      Alaska Airlines Inc.    
## 4 B6      JetBlue Airways         
## 5 DL      Delta Air Lines Inc.    
## 6 EV      ExpressJet Airlines Inc.

Joining the two tables

Before we can join any two tables, we need to identify a variable they have in common that we can use to join them by. This is often referred to as join key.

In both the flights and airlines table, both contain a carrier column that contain the two digit symbol. In this case, carrier is our join key.

There are many types of joins we will discuss today. But the most common one youll use in the real world is called left_join(). You may think of left_join() as a function/tool that augments your primary data with additional data from another table. Since this join adds columns/variables, this is often referred to as a mutating join.

If we want to include the fully spelled out airline name into the flights table, we will use left_join().

Using left_join to combine flights

.extra-tiny[

combined_airline_table <- flights |> 
  left_join(airlines, join_by(carrier)) 
  # flights is the primary table we are working with
  # using carrier as join key, 
  # all variables from airlines are combined with flights

glimpse(combined_airline_table)

Using left_join to combine flights

These five R objects are equivalent (uses different syntax):

# Your book's preferred format:
combined_table <- flights |> 
  left_join(airlines, join_by(carrier)) 

# An alternate version of your book's preferred format:
combined_table <- flights |> 
  left_join(airlines) 
# without join_by(), R makes a guess that you want to use carrier

# This is equivalent
combined_table <- left_join(flights, airlines, join_by(carrier)) 

# This is equivalent
# This is considered 'old notation' by your book
# But most R users like me still uses this over join_by()
combined_table <- left_join(flights, airlines, by = c("carrier"))

# This is equivalent
combined_table <- left_join(flights, airlines)

Preferred syntax from last page?

To me, it doesnt matter. Pick one, then consistently use it.

This reminds me of two deviations within the R community on ggplot:

.pull-left[ .extra-tiny[

# My preferred coding
msleep |>
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = sleep_total, y = sleep_rem)) +
  geom_point()

] ]

.pull-right[ .extra-tiny[

# The way your book taught you
ggplot(data = msleep,
       mapping = aes(x = sleep_total, y = sleep_rem)) +
  geom_point()

] ]

What is the join key here?

left_join(x = table1, y = table2)

All the rows and columns from first referenced table are all kept. Then all information from the second referenced table is then carried into the first table if there is a match on the join key. This is considered a mutating join because you are adding a new column to a base dataset.

Figure 1. Simple example of left_join and output.

left_join(x = table1, y = table2)

All the rows and columns from first referenced table are all kept. Then all information from the second referenced table is then carried into the first table if there is a match on the join key. This is considered a mutating join because you are adding a new column to a base dataset.

.tiny[

joined_table1 <- left_join(superheroes, publishers)
## Joining with `by = join_by(publisher)`
joined_table1
## # A tibble: 7  5
##   name     alignment gender publisher         yr_founded
##   <chr>    <chr>     <chr>  <chr>                  <dbl>
## 1 Magneto  bad       male   Marvel                  1939
## 2 Storm    good      female Marvel                  1939
## 3 Mystique bad       female Marvel                  1939
## 4 Batman   good      male   DC                      1934
## 5 Joker    bad       male   DC                      1934
## 6 Catwoman bad       female DC                      1934
## 7 Hellboy  good      male   Dark Horse Comics         NA

]

inner_join(x = table1, y = table2)

inner_join() returns (1) data rows from the first table if and only if there is a match on the second table on the join key and (2) all columns or variables from the first table. Similar to left_join, columns from the second table is added. Again, this is a mutating join because we are adding variable(s) to the base (first) table.

Figure 1. Simple example of inner_join and output.

inner_join(x = table1, y = table2)

inner_join() returns (1) data rows from the first table if and only if there is a match on the second table on the join key and (2) all columns or variables from the first table. Similar to left_join, columns from the second table is added. Again, this is a mutating join because we are adding variable(s) to the base (first) table.

Notice how the row with Hellboy is no longer present? That is because Dark Horse Comics does not exist as one of the publishers within the publisher table. Hellboy doesnt have a match on the second table, so it is not included.

.tiny[

joined_table2 <- inner_join(superheroes, publishers)
## Joining with `by = join_by(publisher)`
joined_table2
## # A tibble: 6  5
##   name     alignment gender publisher yr_founded
##   <chr>    <chr>     <chr>  <chr>          <dbl>
## 1 Magneto  bad       male   Marvel          1939
## 2 Storm    good      female Marvel          1939
## 3 Mystique bad       female Marvel          1939
## 4 Batman   good      male   DC              1934
## 5 Joker    bad       male   DC              1934
## 6 Catwoman bad       female DC              1934

]

semi_join(x = table1, y = table2)

Return all rows from table1 where there are matching values in table2, but nothing is added from the second table (keeping just columns from table1).

A semi join differs from an inner join because nothing is added from the second table (table2). This is a filtering join (not mutating join). You may think of semi_join() as filtering rows from table1 if and only if they have a match on table2 via a join key.

Figure 3. Simple example of semi_join and output.

semi_join(x = table1, y = table2)

Return all rows from table1 where there are matching values in table2, but nothing is added from the second table (keeping just columns from table1).

A semi join differs from an inner join because nothing is added from the second table (table2). This is a filtering join (not mutating join). You may think of semi_join() as filtering rows from table1 if and only if they have a match on table2 via a join key.

.tiny[

joined_table3 <- semi_join(superheroes, publishers)
## Joining with `by = join_by(publisher)`

## 5 Joker    bad       male   DC       
## 6 Catwoman bad       female DC

anti_join(x = table1, y =table2)

Return all rows from table1 that does not have a match with table2 via a join key, keeping just columns from table1. This is a filtering join (not create a new column).

Figure 4. Simple example of anti_join and output.

anti_join(x = table1, y = table2)

Return all rows from table1 that does not have a match with table2 via a join key, keeping just columns from table1. This is a filtering join (not create a new column).

anti_join(superheroes, publishers)
## Joining with `by = join_by(publisher)`
## # A tibble: 1  4
##   name    alignment gender publisher        
##   <chr>   <chr>     <chr>  <chr>            
## 1 Hellboy good      male   Dark Horse Comics

full_join(x = table1, y = table2)

Returns all columns and rows from table1 and table2. Often times, it actually doesnt produce any meaningful results unless used in extremely specific circumstances (beyond the scope of this course).

Figure 5. Simple example of full_join and output.

full_join(x = table1, y = table2)

Forcing Join

There are times when the tables in your R environment share a join key but have different variable or column names (i.e., this time, while it is called publisher in superheroes_v2, it is now called company in publishers_v2). Now, let us work with superheroes_v2 and publishers_v2:

superheroes_v2 <- tibble::tribble(
       ~name, ~alignment,  ~gender,          ~publisher,
   "Magneto",      "bad",   "male",            "Marvel",
     "Storm",     "good", "female",            "Marvel",
  "Mystique",      "bad", "female",            "Marvel",
    "Batman",     "good",   "male",                "DC",
     "Joker",      "bad",   "male",                "DC",
  "Catwoman",      "bad", "female",                "DC",
   "Hellboy",     "good",   "male", "Dark Horse Comics"
  )

publishers_v2 <- tibble::tribble(
  ~company, ~yr_founded,
        "DC",       1934,
    "Marvel",       1939,
     "Image",       1992
  )

Let us see error produced by R when attempting to join those two

left_join(superheroes_v2, publishers_v2)
## Error in `left_join()`:
## ! `by` must be supplied when `x` and `y` have no common variables.
##  Use `cross_join()` to perform a cross-join.

Dealing with join keys with different names?

Method 1: Rename to make them common.

In the example below, publishers_v2s company variable is renamed to publisher using rename(). The resulting data is saved as publishers_v3. Then we use publishers_v3 within the left_join(). .tiny[

publishers_v3 <- publishers_v2 |> 
  rename(publisher = company)

left_join(superheroes_v2, publishers_v3)
## Joining with `by = join_by(publisher)`
## # A tibble: 7  5
##   name     alignment gender publisher         yr_founded
##   <chr>    <chr>     <chr>  <chr>                  <dbl>
## 1 Magneto  bad       male   Marvel                  1939
## 2 Storm    good      female Marvel                  1939
## 3 Mystique bad       female Marvel                  1939
## 4 Batman   good      male   DC                      1934
## 5 Joker    bad       male   DC                      1934
## 6 Catwoman bad       female DC                      1934
## 7 Hellboy  good      male   Dark Horse Comics         NA

]

Dealing with join keys with different names?

Method 2: Manual specification method using join_by()

You are telling R below that the two tables have a common key but named differently. You are telling R to treat superheroes_v2s publisher and publishers_v2s company as the equivalent join keys. .tiny[

left_join(superheroes_v2, publishers_v2, join_by(publisher == company))
## # A tibble: 7  5
##   name     alignment gender publisher         yr_founded
##   <chr>    <chr>     <chr>  <chr>                  <dbl>
## 1 Magneto  bad       male   Marvel                  1939
## 2 Storm    good      female Marvel                  1939
## 3 Mystique bad       female Marvel                  1939
## 4 Batman   good      male   DC                      1934
## 5 Joker    bad       male   DC                      1934
## 6 Catwoman bad       female DC                      1934
## 7 Hellboy  good      male   Dark Horse Comics         NA

]
